<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-034-574  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 034 574.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Jan 8 1990 v9 n1 p74(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Yates to become head of AFSC. (Air Force Systems Command)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Green, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Air Force Systems CommandManagement of EDPMilitaryCommand and Control SystemsWeaponsEquipment Acquisition.andO;Person:    Yates, Ronald W. (selection and appointment).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Yates to Become Heat of AFSCandM;The Air Force Systems Command (AFSC), said to be a target of forthcomingPentagon budget cuts, will get a new commander later this year.andM;Lt.andP;  Gen.andP;  Ronald W. Yates, currently principal deputy assistant secretary ofthe Air Force for acquisition, will take over the command April 1.andP;  In abrief statement, Yates said that Defense Department budget cuts will makecommand, control, communications and computer systems a higher priority inthe 1990s.andM;Defense Secretary Dick Cheney named Yates to succeed Gen.andP;  Bernard P.andO;Randolph, who has commanded AFSC since July 1987 and is retiring.andP;  Yates willbe replaced by Maj.andP;  Gen.andP;  Thomas R. Ferguson Jr., now at AFSC as deputychief of staff, technology and requirements planning.andM;AFSC, headquarters at Andrews Air Force Base, Md., has a worldwide staff of53,000.andP;  The command develops and acquires many Air Force weapon systems andsome information systems.andM;Through its Electronic Systems Division at Hanscom Air Force Base, Mass.,andO;AFSC oversees the Unified Local Area Network Architecture program by whichAir Force computers can be linked with common components into LANs of varioussizes and types.andP;  Known for its high-technology acquisition specialists, AFSCalso overseas such operations as the Arnold Engineering Development Center inTennessee.andM;In the current belt-tightening DOD atmosphere, AFSC often is rumored to befacing substantial cuts.andP;  Last spring, industry officials said Donald J.andO;Atwood Jr., the deputy secretary of Defense, was considering eliminating AFSCaltogether as a way of removing a layer of bureaucracy in Air Forceacquisitions.andP;  In November, a Pentagon report recommended that as many as5,000 AFSC jobs the eliminated over the next five years.andM;Officials have said that if AFSC were eliminated, the office of the assistantsecretary of the Air Force for acquisition likely would assume the command'sduties.andO;</TEXT></DOC>